<subSubSection id="EBAF651CC23E6F2FFF088B85FB995CFE" box="[227,1034,207,234]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="A30A3697C23E6F2FFF088B85FB995CFE" blockId="15.[227,1034,175,234]" box="[227,1034,207,234]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
H o s t p l a n t s. 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFE7C8B85FDE75CFD" box="[407,628,207,233]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Juniperus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thurifera">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFE7C8B85FDE75CFD" box="[407,628,207,233]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Juniperus thurifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<bibRefCitation id="C7244B66C23E6F2FFD4B8B9AFC6D5CFE" author="Merz, B. &amp; Blasco-Zumeta, J." box="[672,1022,207,234]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="127 - 134" refId="ref14097" refString="Merz, B., Blasco-Zumeta, J. 1995. The fruit flies (Diptera, Tephritidae) of the Monegros region (Zaragoza, Spain), with the record of the host plant of Rhagoletis zernyi Hendel, 1927. Zapateri, Revista Aragonesa de Entomologia. 5, 127 - 134." type="journal article" year="1995">Merz &amp; Blasco-Zumeta, 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph id="A30A3697C23E6F2FFF458A5AFE275D3D" blockId="15.[174,436,271,297]" box="[174,436,271,297]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFF458A5AFE275D3D" bold="true" box="[174,436,271,297]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Phylogenetic analysis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A30A3697C23E6F2FFF088A6AFB3F5DCE" blockId="15.[174,1233,319,1082]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Hulbert’s (2018) multigene molecular analysis grouped the included 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFBF48A6AFF495D6D" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFBF48A6AFB055D4D" box="[1055,1174,319,345]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Rhagoletis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
into ten lineages corresponding to 12 previously established species groups (
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFBB48A0AFF785DAD" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFBB48A0AFB5F5D6D" authorityName="Fallen" authorityYear="1814" box="[1119,1228,351,377]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Tephritis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alternata">alternata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFF458AD5FF605D8D" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[174,243,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerasi">cerasi</taxonomicName>
, meigenii, ferruginea, nova, striatella, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFD298AD5FCAD5D8D" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[706,830,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">juniperina</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFCA68A2AFC345D8D" authorityName="Doane" authorityYear="1899" box="[845,935,383,409]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ribicola">ribicola</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFC5C8A2AFBB65D8D" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[951,1061,383,409]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cingulata">cingulata</taxonomicName>
, suavis, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFB658A2AFF745DAD" baseAuthorityName="Fitch" baseAuthorityYear="1855" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tabellaria">tabellaria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFEC28ACAFE315DAD" baseAuthorityName="Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[297,418,415,441]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomonella">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFEC28ACAFE315DAD" box="[297,418,415,441]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">pomonella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), which mainly correspond to the groups proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="C7244B66C23E6F2FFBD28ACAFB5F5DAE" author="Bush, G. L." box="[1081,1228,415,442]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="431 - 562" refId="ref12251" refString="Bush, G. L. 1966. The taxonomy, cytology, and evolution of the genus Rhagoletis in North America (Diptera, Tephritidae). Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 134, 431 - 562." type="journal article" year="1966">Bush (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="C7244B66C23E6F2FFF458AEAFE165DCE" author="Kandybina, M. N." box="[174,389,447,474]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 212" refId="ref13296" refString="Kandybina, M. N. 1977. The larvae of fruit-flies (Diptera: Tephritidae). Nauka, Leningrad, 1 - 212 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1977">Kandybina (1977)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="C7244B66C23E6F2FFE288AEAFD295DCE" author="Smith, J. J. &amp; Bush, G. L." box="[451,698,447,474]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="187 - 217" refId="ref14669" refString="Smith, J. J., Bush, G. L., 1999. Phylogeny of Carpomyina, emphasizing relationships of the genus Rhagoletis. In: Aluja, M., Norrbom, A. L., eds. Fruit Flies (Tephritidae): Phylogeny and Evolution of Behavior. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 187 - 217." type="book chapter" year="1999">Smith &amp; Bush (1999)</bibRefCitation>
plus the unplaced 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFC7D8A95FC6E5DCD" baseAuthorityName="Osten Sacken" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[918,1021,447,473]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fausta">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFC7D8A95FC6E5DCD" box="[918,1021,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. fausta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFBDC8A95FB365DCD" authorityName=": Merz" authorityYear="1994" box="[1079,1189,447,473]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batava">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFBDC8A95FB365DCD" box="[1079,1189,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. batava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A30A3697C23E6F2FFF088A8AFBFC5E6E" blockId="15.[174,1233,319,1082]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Our analyses here is based on the 85 individuals from Hulbert (2018) plus 
<specimenCount id="B5B3FD1EC23E6F2FFBA38A8AFF7E5E0E" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFEFA8955FEE15E0D" authorityName="Korneyev &amp; Smith &amp; Hulbert &amp; Frey &amp; Korneyev" authorityYear="2022" box="[273,370,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merzi">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFEFA8955FEE15E0D" box="[273,370,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. merzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<specimenCount id="B5B3FD1EC23E6F2FFE418AAAFDF45E0D" box="[426,615,511,537]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFD608955FD0E5E0D" box="[651,669,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R</emphasis>
. sp. nr. 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFD138955FCE15E0D" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[760,882,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFD138955FCE15E0D" box="[760,882,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, using the same 4270 bp from the COI, 
<collectingCountry id="DBA27607C23E6F2FFECB894AFEF35E2D" box="[288,352,543,569]" name="Chad" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">CAD</collectingCountry>
, 28S, period, and AATS genes used in Hulbert (2018). The taxon sample includes two outgroup species (
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFDCA896AFD6A5E4D" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[545,761,575,601]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Anastrepha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ludens">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFDCA896AFD6A5E4D" box="[545,761,575,601]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Anastrepha ludens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFCD8896AFBA65E4D" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[819,1077,575,601]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Euphranta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFCD8896AFBA65E4D" box="[819,1077,575,601]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Euphranta canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), one species of 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFF278935FED55E6E" box="[204,326,608,634]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Carpomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFF278935FED55E6E" box="[204,326,608,634]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Carpomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 35 species representing most of the species groups of 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFC1A890AFBFB5E6D" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1862" box="[1009,1128,607,633]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFC1A890AFBFB5E6D" box="[1009,1128,607,633]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Rhagoletis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A30A3697C23E6F2FFF08892AFD705F8D" blockId="15.[174,1233,319,1082]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The Bayesian analysis recovered a monophyletic cluster with high support, containing the 
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFF3389F5FD0B5EAD" box="[216,664,671,697]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
suavis, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFEC089CAFE0A5EAD" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[299,409,671,697]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cingulata">cingulata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFE4F89CAFDB35EAD" baseAuthorityName="Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[420,544,671,697]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomonella">pomonella</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFDC289CAFD0B5EAD" baseAuthorityName="Fitch" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[553,664,671,697]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tabellaria">tabellaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFD3D89F5FCC35EAD" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[726,848,672,697]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFD3D89F5FCC35EAD" box="[726,848,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups plus the unplaced species 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFF458995FE855ECD" baseAuthorityName="Osten Sacken" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[174,278,703,729]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fausta">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFF458995FE855ECD" box="[174,278,703,729]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. fausta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFEBE8995FE555ECD" authorityName=": Merz" authorityYear="1994" box="[341,454,703,729]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batava">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFEBE8995FE555ECD" box="[341,454,703,729]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. batava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="3B8E2A12C23E6F2FFE3389EAFD8B5ECE" box="[472,536,703,730]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[166,199,1311,1333]" captionTargetBox="[166,1243,174,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-11@16.[239,1269,174,1855]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 9. Bayesian phylogeny of Rhagoletis inferred from an alignment of 4270 bp of five genes (COI, CAD, ribo- somal 28S, period and AATS) using MrBayes, and Max- imum-Likelihood using MEGA 11. The first number on each branch is the bootstrap support from ML analysis; the second number represents posterior probability from Bayesian inference (BI). Asterisks (*)over branch- es indicate a Bayesian posterior probability of 1.0 and 100 % bootstrap support for the clade. Dash (- /) means that the clade inferred by MrBayes was not recovered by the ML analysis. Grey background shows position of the “core Nearctic taxa” (Smith et al., 2006). The bold numbers and color rectangles indicate species groups as follows:1 —alternata group,2— cerasigroup,3— clus- ter of ferruginea +nova + striatella groups, 4 — meigenii group, 5 — cingulata group, 6 — suavis group, 7 — ribi- cola group (sensu Bush, 1966), 8 — pomonella group, 9 — tabellaria group, 10 — juniperina group. Abbrevia- tions:NA — Nearctic Region, PA — Palaearctic Region. Inlay shows relationships within the juniperina group." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462321" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462321/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">fig. 9</figureCitation>
). All the juniper-associated species form a well-supported monophyletic lineage corresponding to the 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFD5489B5FCAA5EED" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[703,825,736,761]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFD5489B5FCAA5EED" box="[703,825,736,761]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group within the clade described above. This includes both Nearctic (
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFDB18855FD665F0D" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[602,757,768,793]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFDB18855FD665F0D" box="[602,757,768,793]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and undescribed species 
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFBCF8855FBA55F0D" box="[1060,1078,768,793]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R</emphasis>
. sp. nr. 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFB7C8855FF6A5F2D" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFB7C8855FF6A5F2D" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and Palaearctic species (
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFDCF8875FD475F2D" box="[548,724,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavigenualis">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFDCF8875FD475F2D" box="[548,724,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. flavigenualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFCE68875FCFD5F2D" authorityName="Korneyev &amp; Smith &amp; Hulbert &amp; Frey &amp; Korneyev" authorityYear="2022" box="[781,878,800,825]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merzi">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFCE68875FCFD5F2D" box="[781,878,800,825]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. merzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It is interesting that 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFB9B8875FB435F2D" authorityName="Korneyev &amp; Smith &amp; Hulbert &amp; Frey &amp; Korneyev" authorityYear="2022" box="[1136,1232,800,825]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merzi">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFB9B8875FB435F2D" box="[1136,1232,800,825]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. merzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more similar to the Nearctic taxa (
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFDB28815FD615F4D" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[601,754,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFDB28815FD615F4D" box="[601,754,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R. juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFD148815FC8B5F4D" box="[767,792,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">R.</emphasis>
sp. near 
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFC6B8815FC695F4D" authorityName="Marcovitch" authorityYear="1915" box="[896,1018,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juniperina">
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFC6B8815FC695F4D" box="[896,1018,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">juniperina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in both morphological characters (wing pattern, occiput, mesonotum and leg coloration) and molecular sequences than to the Palearctic 
<emphasis id="91C1EA85C23E6F2FFDC188D5FD705F8D" box="[554,739,895,921]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName id="64B54D14C23E6F2FFDC188D5FD4D5F8D" box="[554,734,895,921]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Rhagoletis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavigenualis">R. flavigenualis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A30A3697C23E6F2FFF0888CAFDEE582E" blockId="15.[174,1233,319,1082]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The Maximum Likelihood tree has a similar topology to that obtained with the Bayesian analysis, yet with some notable differences that mostly concern position of some basal groups (
<figureCitation id="3B8E2A12C23E6F2FFEE5888AFED85FEE" box="[270,331,991,1018]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[166,199,1311,1333]" captionTargetBox="[166,1243,174,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-11@16.[239,1269,174,1855]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 9. Bayesian phylogeny of Rhagoletis inferred from an alignment of 4270 bp of five genes (COI, CAD, ribo- somal 28S, period and AATS) using MrBayes, and Max- imum-Likelihood using MEGA 11. The first number on each branch is the bootstrap support from ML analysis; the second number represents posterior probability from Bayesian inference (BI). Asterisks (*)over branch- es indicate a Bayesian posterior probability of 1.0 and 100 % bootstrap support for the clade. Dash (- /) means that the clade inferred by MrBayes was not recovered by the ML analysis. Grey background shows position of the “core Nearctic taxa” (Smith et al., 2006). The bold numbers and color rectangles indicate species groups as follows:1 —alternata group,2— cerasigroup,3— clus- ter of ferruginea +nova + striatella groups, 4 — meigenii group, 5 — cingulata group, 6 — suavis group, 7 — ribi- cola group (sensu Bush, 1966), 8 — pomonella group, 9 — tabellaria group, 10 — juniperina group. Abbrevia- tions:NA — Nearctic Region, PA — Palaearctic Region. Inlay shows relationships within the juniperina group." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462321" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462321/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">fig. 9</figureCitation>
). The 
